  "prompt": "Where can I find comedic monologues from published plays?",
  "response": "Here are some good resources for finding comedic monologues from published plays:\n\n1. Drama bookstores and websites\n- Samuel French Bookstore\n- Dramatists Play Service\n- Broadway Play Publishing\n\n2. Online monologue collections\n- Monologue Blogger\n- Actors Access\n- New Play Exchange\n\n3. Recommended play collections \n- \"Monologues for Actors\" series\n- \"Contemporary Comedic Monologues\" compilations\n- Anthology books of comedy plays\n\n4. Playwright websites\n- Many playwrights have sample monologues on their personal websites\n- Look for comedic playwrights like Neil Simon, Christopher Durang, etc.\n\nTips:\n- Always get permission before performing\n- Check copyright restrictions \n- Purchase scripts when possible\n- Credit the playwright appropriately\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these suggestions?",
